`Take the JP Morgan situation. Ye said he moved 140 million dollars into Chase and could not get a meeting with Jamie Dimon. He named a specific person, Jing Ulrich, who served on the Adidas Supervisory Board while holding a senior executive position as Vice Chairman of Investment Banking at JP Morgan, and said the conflict of interest was why he was being shut out of deal flow. He said the system was designed to keep people like him out of the rooms where real financial architecture happens. When you check this, The dual role was real. Jing Ulrich did hold positions at both companies simultaneously. Whether you call that a board interlock or an executive-board overlap depends on how precisely you want to define it, but the structural relationship Ye was pointing at existed. The bank sent a formal letter ending the Yeezy LLC relationship on September 20, 2022, which was before the antisemitic posts, not after. Ye had also appeared on CNBC and Bloomberg eight days earlier, publicly criticizing Jamie Dimon by name and saying he was moving his money out. Whether the bank acted first or simply formalized a departure Ye had already announced is not entirely clear from the outside. What is clear is that the split had nothing to do with the antisemitic statements that came later. The observation about how private banking gatekeeps access at the ultra-high-net-worth level was accurate. The explanation he later attached to it was not.`
