`This is where it gets complicated and where I want to be precise. In the banking, fashion, and retail conflicts, the specific executives Ye was fighting were Jamie Dimon, who is Greek Orthodox; Bill Grous, who is Greek Orthodox; Jing Ulrich, who is Beijing-born Chinese; Kasper R\u00F8rsted at Adidas, who is Danish; Mark Breitbard at Gap; Daniel Cherry III at Adidas, who is Black. None of them were Jewish. But in the music industry, some of his adversaries were. Lucian Grainge, the CEO of Universal Music Group, which controlled Ye\u2019s catalog for most of his career, is Jewish. Scooter Braun, who became one of the most contested figures in artist ownership disputes, the same person Taylor Swift fought publicly, is Jewish. Ye\u2019s entire recording career was spent under the Universal umbrella. If you are looking for where the pattern began forming in his mind, it was probably there, in the specific industry where the executives who controlled his masters and his revenue did fit the demographic profile he later projected onto everyone.`,
`But this is exactly where observation becomes distortion. The fact that some executives in one industry share a demographic background does not mean that demographic background is the cause. The music industry\u2019s ownership structure exploits every artist regardless of who sits in the executive suite. The 16 cents per streaming dollar going to artists is not a Jewish policy. It is an industry structure. Ye\u2019s early contracts with Roc-A-Fella, under Jay-Z, who is Black, gave the label ownership of his first six albums in perpetuity. The exploitation is structural. It runs on contract law and leverage asymmetry, not on ethnicity. What Ye did was take a real observation from one industry, a real grievance with specific people, and generalize it into an explanation for every gatekeeping experience he had across banking, fashion, retail, and politics. And the generalization was wrong. Not because the individual grievances were fake, but because the connective framework was. The correct explanation for what he experienced is institutional power and class-based gatekeeping. It cuts across every demographic. His own conflicts proved this, if he had looked at the full picture instead of selecting the pieces that confirmed what he already believed.`
