`Adidas has the product. They have the supply chain. They have billions in physical inventory sitting in warehouses. Ye has five letters and a fraction of his former wealth. My father told me a story once about something that happened in the car industry. The way he explained it stayed with me longer than most things people say.`,
`In 1998, one of the most prestigious car brands in history was put up for sale. The company that owned it could no longer afford to keep it. Two German automakers saw the opportunity and both wanted it. This was not a quiet transaction. This was a public bidding war for the right to own a name that had meant the pinnacle of luxury since 1906. Both companies understood what they were bidding on: the factory in England where these cars had been built by hand for half a century, the engineers who knew how to build them, the production line, the supplier relationships, the active models, the heritage. Whoever won the bid would inherit all of it.`,
`One of the two had been supplying engines and components to the brand for years. They had the relationship. They had the inside position. They put in an offer of 340 million pounds. It should have been enough. It was not. The other company came in at the last minute with 430 million pounds. The board accepted the higher bid. It was not close.`,
`The winner walked away with everything. The building. The production line. The engineers, some of whom had spent their entire careers stitching leather and fitting panels to tolerances measured in fractions of a millimeter. The paint booths, the tools, the existing car designs, the active models still in production, and a second luxury brand that had been manufactured under the same roof since 1931. The hood ornament. The radiator grille shape. Every physical thing that made this car what it was. The press covered it as a decisive victory. One of the most storied names in automotive history had been acquired, and the winner had the keys to the building where the cars were made.`,
`The company that lost had nothing. They had been outbid, outmaneuvered, and shut out of the deal entirely. As it happened, the name itself, the actual trademark, had not been part of the sale. It was owned by a separate aerospace company that had licensed it into the car business decades earlier. The aerospace company had no interest in selling it to the winner of the bid. They had a better relationship with the loser. So the loser bought the trademark for 40 million pounds. No factory. No engineers. No designs. No production line. No supply chain. No active models. No heritage in any physical sense. A word and a logo. The winner now had a factory full of cars they could not put the original name on without the loser\u2019s permission. It was a nuisance. Maybe the winner would eventually pay a premium to buy the name. Maybe it would be an irritation and nothing more.`
