`The Oval Office meeting was the clearest example. On October 11, 2018, Ye sat with Trump for a televised session. Rolling Stone called it \u201Cthe craziest Oval Office performance of all time.\u201D CNN\u2019s Don Lemon said he could not even watch it. That is what was covered. That is what the world saw. Almost nobody listened to what he actually said.`,
`He said: \u201CYou have to bring manufacturing onshore. Not even shore, into the core. Chicago is the core of Middle America.\u201D He connected the collapse of manufacturing directly to incarceration: when there are no factories, people end up in the cheapest factory ever built, which is the prison system. That is not an incoherent observation. That is a causal chain documented in economic research. On April 2, 2025, nearly seven years after Ye said this in the Oval Office, Trump announced \u201CLiberation Day,\u201D a sweeping tariff executive order imposing a 10% baseline on imports from nearly all countries, 34% on China, 20% on the European Union. The explicit, stated goal of the policy was reshoring American manufacturing. The White House cited 5 million manufacturing jobs lost between 1997 and 2024. It became the centerpiece of American trade policy. The observation that Ye made in 2018, the one the media treated as rambling, became the animating logic of the largest shift in US economic strategy in decades. He pushed back on Trump\u2019s endorsement of stop-and-frisk: \u201CThe problem is illegal guns. Illegal guns is the problem, not legal guns.\u201D He proposed that Trump wear a modified MAGA hat alongside Colin Kaepernick at the Super Bowl as a unity gesture. He talked about prison reform. The First Step Act, bipartisan criminal justice legislation, was signed into law two months later, in December 2018.`,
`And then there was the hat. He told Trump to take the word \u201CAgain\u201D off \u201CMake America Great Again.\u201D He said the word hurts, specifically for Black Americans, because it points backward to a time that was not great for them. That pain is real and it does not need Ye to validate it. But what he proposed was not just a racial correction. He proposed \u201CMake America Great,\u201D and the reasoning underneath it, if you listen carefully, goes further than most people gave him credit for. Most people who saw this clip filed it away as another racial grievance from a man who had been saying controversial things about race all week. Same conversation, nothing new, move on. But Ye was not just saying the word \u201Cagain\u201D is offensive. He was saying the word is wrong. \u201CAgain\u201D assumes there is something behind you worth returning to. Remove it and what Ye is left pointing at is the only tense that actually matters. The past is gone. It cannot be acted on. The future has not arrived. It cannot be acted on either. The only place where anything can be built, fixed, or changed is the present, and the present does not care what came before it. It only asks what you are willing to do now. I have noticed that most traditions that take this question seriously, whether religious, philosophical, or practical, arrive at some version of the same answer. Ye arrived at it in the Oval Office, in his own language, and it was treated as part of the rambling. Columbia Journalism Review later criticized the media for covering the meeting as spectacle rather than policy. By then it did not matter. The clip had already become the joke.`
