`I think this is what people miss about Ye. Not that he is always right. He is not. But that the mode he operates in is not the mode people are listening for. People listen for arguments. Ye does not make arguments. He makes observations, and he makes them from a place that is closer to raw perception than to structured rhetoric, and when the observation does not come out clean, he does not go back and fix it. He pushes forward. And the world, which rewards packaging above almost everything else, treats the lack of packaging as evidence that there is nothing inside.`,
`And here is where I think Ye makes a genuine mistake, not a moral one but a practical one. It seems to me that he disregards the things our society considers valuable in how ideas are presented. The framing, the awareness of who is in the room, the calibration of what people are ready to hear. And from what I can see, it is genuine disregard. I do not think he is trying and failing. I think he does not believe the packaging should matter. In some ideal world maybe it should not. But that is not the world we operate in. What a society values changes. There was a time when physical strength was the thing that mattered most, when it determined who led, who ate, who survived. That time passed. Right now, in this particular moment of history, intellect and the ability to articulate it are what carry weight. The person who can think clearly and communicate that thinking precisely is the person the current world rewards. That is not permanent. It is not moral law. It is just what happens to be true right now. And the things that are true right now are the things you have to work with if you want to move through the world without unnecessary friction. Societal rules and opinions are not right or wrong in some absolute sense. They are the operating system. They are how things actually move between people. If you want any good fortune with the people around you, any ability to shift their thinking or build something alongside them, you have to work within that system. Not because it deserves your submission but because it is the medium you are working in, the way gravity is the medium a builder works in whether he respects it or not. You do not have to go silent. Silence might be worse than bad packaging, because at least bad packaging contains something. But there is a way to speak where both audiences hear you: the people who will only ever read the surface, and the people willing to go deeper. You make the surface clean enough that the first group does not shut you out before they arrive at anything, and underneath it you place the real thing for the people who will look. People always read the superficial layer first. Always. If the surface repels them, they never reach what is underneath, no matter how real it is. I do not think Ye cares about this. I am not saying he must change. I am saying his ideas would travel further and more of what he actually sees would survive contact with the world.`
