`There is something in Ye that I think most people will never see because they stopped looking after the first thing that offended them. He cares about his people. His anger at the music industry, at the contracts that keep artists from owning anything, at the corporate structures that extract value from Black creativity and return almost none of it, that anger came from somewhere real. He watched it happen. He experienced it. In the streaming economy, for every dollar of revenue, the artist receives roughly 16 cents. The label keeps 64 cents. His early contracts with Roc-A-Fella confirmed that his first six albums were the label\u2019s property, in perpetuity, worldwide. That is standard. The standard itself is what he was fighting. He tried to tear the structure down with his hands instead of with a blueprint, and the result was chaos, but the impulse was not hatred. The impulse was protection. He was not against any group of people because of what they are. He was against specific mechanisms that he had experienced from the inside. But because he does not translate, because emotion takes him to the extreme rather than the optimal, what arrived in public was something that sounded like hatred. And once it sounded like hatred, the original observation was dead. Nobody goes back to check the foundation of a building that is already on fire.`
