`But this is also where the anger itself failed him, not just the delivery of it. Ye has said it himself: to have God inside you is to act out of love, not out of hate. He has said this. And I believe he means it. But meaning something and living it in the moments that matter are different things, and when those moments came, rage took over. You do not get anything by displaying rage onto the people who do wrong. You do not correct them. You do not expose them. You do not change the structure. You only disrupt your own inner peace, and in doing so you hand your enemies exactly the weapon they need to dismiss everything you were trying to say. The people who were exploiting artists did not suffer when Ye went on his public tirades. Ye suffered. His partnerships collapsed. His credibility collapsed. He lost 1.5 billion dollars in a matter of weeks. The structures he was raging against are still standing, untouched. Rage as a public strategy does not dismantle systems. It dismantles the person who cannot contain it. Jay-Z saw the same system. He responded by building Roc Nation, which now operates a distribution platform where artists retain 85% of their earnings and keep ownership of their masters. That structure did not exist from the beginning. Roc Nation started with deals closer to industry standard and moved toward artist ownership over time, most recently through a distribution dashboard launched in late 2025. The trajectory matters more than any single number. Jay-Z started inside the same system Ye was fighting and restructured his way out of it over two decades. His net worth reached 2.5 billion dollars, and his music catalog accounts for less than 4% of it. The music made him visible. The ownership made him wealthy. Same observations. Different discipline.`
