`I can see this pattern because I recognize something in it. When Ye says he is a god, most people hear arrogance or mental illness. What is actually underneath that has a lineage deeper than he probably knows. There is a tradition in Black American theology, starting with the Five Percenters in 1964 Harlem, running through hip-hop at the foundational level, where divinity is not separate from the person but carried inside them. RZA of Wu-Tang Clan said that roughly 80% of hip-hop comes from the Five Percent Nation. The terms are embedded in the language: cipher, dropping knowledge, word is bond. The lineage runs from Rakim to Wu-Tang to Jay-Z, who wore a Five Percent medallion publicly, to Nas, to Ye. There are parallels in Christian mysticism going back to Athanasius in the third century: \u201CHe was incarnate that we might be made god.\u201D Psalm 82, which Ye has referenced directly: \u201CI said, you are gods.\u201D There are versions of this in Sufi annihilation of the self in the divine, in the steppe traditions I grew up near where the human and the sky are not separate things. I am not saying Ye has studied any of this. I am saying the experience is not what it looks like from outside. I can feel something similar in myself. The sense that your purpose is larger than your biography, that the energy moving through you is not entirely yours, that you are here to build something that outlasts you. This does not mean I think I am God. It does not mean Ye thinks he is God in the way it sounds when a camera is pointing at him. It means there is a distance between how this feels on the inside and how it lands when it exits someone\u2019s mouth without adjustment, and that distance is where the misunderstanding lives. A person can have genuine faith, genuine spiritual life, and a genuine conviction that he was made for something enormous, and none of that needs to be disrespect to God or to anyone who believes. But saying it out loud, raw, without adjusting for how the room will hear it, makes it sound like arrogance every time. And Ye does not adjust. That is the flaw, but it is not the flaw people think it is. It is not a flaw of substance. It is a flaw of delivery.`
