`The Virgil Abloh situation revealed something structural. They met at a Chicago print shop around 2002. They interned together at Fendi in Rome for 500 dollars a month. Virgil designed album covers, creative directed the DONDA agency, shaped the visual world of Watch the Throne and My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy. Then in 2018, Louis Vuitton named Virgil artistic director of menswear, the first person of African descent in that role. Ye has said that Bernard Arnault offered him the position first, that Alexandre Arnault told him his father never goes back on his word, and that three months later the offer was pulled. LVMH has never publicly confirmed or denied this. Virgil himself called Ye two minutes before the appointment went public. Whether Ye\u2019s account is fully accurate or colored by the pain he later described feeling, the dynamic it points to is consistent with what happened next. The fashion establishment chose the version of Ye\u2019s aesthetic that came in a package the institution could absorb. Virgil was the translator. Ye was the originator. And institutions almost always choose the translator, because the translator does not make the board uncomfortable. He takes the vision someone else created and presents it in a way that does not threaten anything. This is not a fashion problem. It runs through every industry I have looked at. Tesla and Edison. Jack Kirby and Stan Lee. Philo Farnsworth and David Sarnoff. The person who sees something first and the person who makes it legible to the room are almost never the same person, and the room almost always rewards the second one.`
