`The Hitler comments I cannot find anything underneath. I looked. I wanted to find the same structure I found underneath the banking critique and the BLM critique: a real observation that arrived in a form nobody could accept. Something about how historical conditions create leaders, how humiliation generates a desire for restoration that is comprehensible without being admirable. Historians make exactly this analysis without anyone calling them anything. But what Ye actually said, going back to at least 2015, when he called Hitler a \u201Cmarketing genius\u201D on a business call, through 2018, when TMZ edited out his saying \u201CI love Hitler, I love Nazis\u201D from the same visit that produced \u201Cslavery was a choice,\u201D through December 2022, when he sat on InfoWars and said \u201Cevery human being has something of value that they brought to the table, especially Hitler,\u201D and then \u201CI like Hitler,\u201D and then \u201CI am a Nazi,\u201D and then denied that six million people were killed, this was not fumbled analysis. It was a pattern stretching across seven years. The word \u201Cespecially\u201D before Hitler inverts any reading that tries to frame it as a universalist statement about human value.`,
`There is one thing, though, that I think is worth sitting with. Ye has said, many times, that we need to love everybody. And I think there is something real in that, not because everyone deserves love, and not because the people who committed the worst acts in history deserve forgiveness. But because carrying hatred for anyone, even someone who earned it, does not damage them. It damages you. Refusing to forgive is not a punishment you impose on the other person. It is a weight you carry yourself. The act of letting go is not about what they deserve. It is about what you are willing to hold inside you for the rest of your life. I think that idea, on its own, is worth listening to. But Ye did not stay there. If he had held to his own principle, the conversation about love and forgiveness would have been the point, and it would have been a powerful one. Instead, what followed was the opposite of what he was preaching. The statements about Jewish people were not love. They were not forgiveness. They were not even the unfiltered honesty he seemed to think they were. They were the principle collapsing under its own weight because the person holding it had not internalized it deeply enough to live it when it mattered.`
