`The undisputed heavyweight champion of the world is being confronted at a McDonald\u2019s on Khreshchatyk in Kyiv. A stranger decides to start something with Oleksandr Usyk. Usyk does not square up. He refuses to engage, and the way he does it is almost playful. Not performed calm, not gritted-teeth restraint. Closer to amusement. The comments under the video always say the same thing: respect, discipline, he knows what his hands can do. But I think they are slightly wrong about what is happening. Discipline implies resistance. It implies Usyk wanted to hit the man and chose not to. I do not think that is what is going on. I think the provocation does not register as a threat. The distance between their capabilities is so vast that the situation is closer to comedy than conflict. There is nothing to resist because there is nothing to resist against.`,
`I notice this in smaller places. When my brother gets frustrated and swings at me with everything he has, it can genuinely hurt. He is not weak. He connects and the impact is real. But I feel no animosity. No stress. No activation of whatever it is inside a person that converts a hit into a reason to hit back. I absorb it and I feel something closer to warmth than anything else. He is my brother. He is frustrated. The pain is just pain. It does not become a story about disrespect or dominance or someone crossing a line. It stays exactly what it is: a kid who is upset, doing the only thing he knows how to do with the feeling. And I do not need discipline to avoid responding. The thought does not form. There is nothing at stake.`,
`Or consider something else. There is always someone, in a classroom, in a gym, in some public space, who decides to perform dominance. He talks louder than he needs to. He disrespects people who are not in a position to respond. He postures. And when you watch him, if you are honest about what you feel, it is not anger. It is something closer to pity. He is, and there is no kind way to say this, pathetic. Not because he is a bad person. Because the performance is so transparent, so obviously compensatory, that you can see right through it to the insecurity underneath. And you are not going to do anything about it. Not because you are choosing restraint. Because he is not worth your time, your energy, your life force. Why would you? What would it accomplish? Let him be. He will eventually try this with someone who cannot control himself, and the lesson will arrive without your involvement. They always learn eventually. It is never from the person who could have taught them gently. It is always from the person who did not care enough to be gentle.`,
`But if you look at yourself carefully, honestly, the picture changes. The times you actually get angry, the times the feeling is real and hot and present, are not the times someone beneath you is being foolish. Those moments produce nothing. The times you get angry are the times you feel genuine threat. Real danger. Someone who is clearly strong enough, dominant enough, capable enough that the disrespect actually lands. That is when the anger arrives. Because the anger was never about the disrespect. It was about whether the person delivering it has the power to back it up. When they do not, you feel nothing. When they do, you feel everything. Which means the anger was fear the entire time. It was always fear.`
