`I think that is true far more broadly than most people are willing to admit.`,
`The amygdala, the region of the brain that processes threat, does not cleanly separate fear from aggression. They share the same physiological activation, channeled in different directions. The person who lashes out at a stranger, the driver who screams through glass at another driver, the man who punches a wall when he receives bad news: all of them are afraid. The anger is the fear searching for somewhere to go. And because anger feels powerful while fear feels weak, the person experiencing it rarely recognizes what is actually happening. They believe they are being strong. They are terrified. The correlation is consistent enough that you can almost use it as a diagnostic. The more violent and reactive a person is, the more frightened they are. The rage is proportional to the insecurity underneath it.`,
`Now look at the other side of the Usyk video. The stranger. Why is he there? What is he doing? He walked into a restaurant, found someone, and decided to manufacture a confrontation out of nothing. Watch the body language of anyone who starts a fight they did not need to start. The jaw is tight. The voice is too loud. The movements are jerky, not controlled. Everything about the performance is defensive. He is projecting danger because he feels danger. The aggression is not coming from power. It is coming from its absence. And Usyk, treating the whole thing like a joke, is the cleanest possible proof. He does not feel what the stranger is trying to make him feel, because the stranger does not have the capability to make him feel it. The threat is not real. So the anger does not arrive. Because anger only arrives when the threat is real.`
