`I see the same pattern in individual lives, compressed into shorter timescales but structurally identical. Consider the difference between the rapper who just got his first hit and the family that has held power for centuries. The rapper is loud. He signals wealth on every available surface. Chains, cars, visible consumption on social media, confrontation as personal brand. This is not celebration. This is reassurance. The position feels new, feels precarious, and the display exists to convince both the audience and the displayer that the position is real. The royal family does not do any of this. Not because they are better people, and not because restraint is their strategy. It simply does not occur to them. The position is so old and so settled that advertising it would feel absurd. They do not think about their status the way you do not think about the fact that you have bones. It is just there.`,
`The most violent and brutal, the most aggressively dominant, are always the ones who have not been in position long enough. Always. This holds for species and it holds for people and it holds for institutions. The ruthless calm of the wolf is the product of deep tenure. The frantic aggression of the newcomer is the product of its absence. And humans, both as a species and often as individuals, are almost always the newcomer. We are almost always still proving it.`,
`I do not think we have the capacity to transcend this entirely. We cannot override millions of years of evolutionary mismatch through willpower alone. We are running on hardware that was built for a different position in the hierarchy, and no amount of philosophy will rewrite the firmware. But I think we can close the gap faster than biology would on its own. That is what culture is for. That is what discipline is for. That is what the deliberate structuring of your own psychology is for. Not to escape nature, but to align with it more quickly than the default rate.`
