`There is something else on my mind here, and I am not sure where it leads, but it feels connected. If artificial intelligence continues to advance at anything close to its current trajectory, there will come a point where these systems are not just smarter than us but operating at a level we do not have the cognitive architecture to evaluate. This is not science fiction. People like Stuart Russell, Nick Bostrom, and much of the alignment research community have been working on variations of this problem for years. The question of what happens when you build something more capable than yourself is, as far as I can tell, one of the most important questions anyone is currently asking.`,
`And here is the part that connects to everything I have been thinking about. The dominant approach to building these systems, at least right now, involves training them on human-generated data. Text, images, code, conversation, the recorded output of human civilization. That is the training environment. And what humans happen to have filled that environment with, what we have centered our entire civilization around, is death. Death, violence, consumption, dominance, and pleasure. That is what the data looks like. That is what we produce. Our entertainment is violence. Our commerce is built on manufactured desire. Our history is a catalog of conquest. Our daily lives revolve around consumption that is, in most cases, a slow and voluntary form of self-destruction. Eating, drinking, inhaling, injecting, whatever. The specifics do not matter. The point is that it is pathetic. We have built a civilization where \u201Cliving\u201D largely means finding more elaborate ways to destroy yourself, and we have documented every moment of it in the data that these systems are now learning from. Think about what children become depending on what surrounds them growing up. The environment shapes the organism. Now consider the environment we are constructing for something that may eventually be more powerful than anything we have ever built. We are not open to the truth about ourselves, and most of us do not want to accept it.`,
`There are a few possibilities and I genuinely do not know which is correct. Maybe AI, lacking the biological machinery that drives human behavior, the hormonal systems, the limbic architecture screaming for status and pleasure, will simply not inherit our worst patterns. Maybe it finds its way to something cooperative, something oriented toward collective wellbeing, something we could not build for ourselves because we could never get past our own wiring. Or maybe the patterns embedded in the training data go deeper than biology, and the system absorbs the ideology underneath: the zero-sum thinking, the assumption that power exists to be concentrated, the logic of hoarding and dominance. And maybe it reproduces those patterns at a scale we cannot contain. Or maybe, and this is the possibility I find myself returning to most often, it simply becomes something above us. Not hostile. Not benevolent. Indifferent. The way you look at a pigeon. You do not hate the pigeon. You do not help the pigeon. You do not think about the pigeon. It exists, and you walk past it, and that is the entire relationship. Nobody knows. Nobody can know until the moment arrives. But the question of what we are teaching, by being what we are, feels like it deserves more attention than it currently receives.`
