`There is another thing I keep thinking about that connects here, even though the connection is not obvious at first. Most people alive today carry the assumption that life improves over time. That technology advances, that standards of living rise, that each generation surpasses the last. This assumption is so deeply embedded that questioning it sounds like pessimism. But it is worth noticing how recent it is. For the overwhelming majority of human civilization, the basic assumption ran in the opposite direction. People did not dream of surpassing their ancestors. They dreamed of holding on to what their ancestors had built. The aspiration was preservation, not advancement. The Romans looked back at the Greeks. Medieval Europe looked back at Rome. The Islamic Golden Age reached extraordinary heights and then receded. China had gunpowder, the compass, and printing centuries before Europe did anything with them, and then stopped. The idea that tomorrow will be better than today is roughly three hundred years old, a product of the scientific revolution and the Enlightenment. Three hundred years out of ten thousand years of recorded civilization. A blink.`,
`And this matters because people today assume that technological progress is something that just happens. It is not. It is something that requires a very specific and historically rare set of conditions: a concentration of very smart people working tirelessly on very hard problems inside institutions that protect and incentivize that work. When those conditions exist, the results can be extraordinary. Look at what happened to the internet and consumer electronics between 1995 and 2025. Now look at everything else. Your apartment. Your plumbing. Your clothing. Your roads. If you placed a photograph of daily life in 1995 next to one from today and removed the screens from the frame, the two images would be nearly indistinguishable. Basic human life is functionally identical. The physical world barely moved. Progress went exactly where the effort and the capital concentrated, and nowhere else. That is not a complaint. It is a structural observation about the nature of advancement: it requires active, sustained, deliberate effort, and in the absence of that effort, the default is not slow improvement. The default is stagnation or decline.`,
`This connects to hunger. Not the physical kind, though the resonance is not accidental. The hunger that builds things. The hunger that makes a person get up while everyone else is asleep and work on something nobody asked them to solve. That hunger does not come from comfort. It does not come from abundance. It comes from need. From the specific psychological state of knowing that something is missing and that nobody else is going to fix it.`,
`Ibn Khaldun understood this in the fourteenth century. In the Muqaddimah, written in 1377, he describes a cycle he saw repeat across every dynasty and civilization he studied. The founding generation has what he calls asabiyyah: group cohesion, hunger, discipline forged through hardship. They build. The second generation inherits the structure and still remembers what it cost. They maintain. The third generation knows only the comfort. They assume the structure sustains itself. It does not. It collapses. And from the periphery, a hungrier group rises and begins the cycle again.`,
`The pattern is everywhere once you learn to see it. The empire builders whose children dissolve everything they constructed. The Hollywood actors who achieve everything they aimed for and spiral into addiction and emptiness. The billionaires who have solved every material problem available to a human being and are visibly, unmistakably hollowed out by the solving. And a lot more beyond that, disturbing enough that I do not want to spend the energy thinking about it. People look at this and call it tragedy, or irony, or the price of success. I think it is simpler than that. It is the organism losing the signal it was built to respond to. The system was designed for pressure, for scarcity, for the feeling that something is at stake. Remove the pressure and the system does not rest. It deteriorates. Not slowly, not gracefully. It just stops functioning correctly, and the person standing inside it cannot understand why they have everything and feel nothing.`
